<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading"><a></a>Dog Years: The 5 Stages of Your Pet=
=E2=80=99s Life</h2>



<p>Sadly, dogs age more quickly than humans do. You may have heard that eve=
ry year of a dog=E2=80=99s life accounts for seven dog years. However, this=
 is not necessarily always the case. This is because dogs age at different =
rates depending on their size.</p>



<p><strong>On average, small and medium-sized dogs age more slowly than lar=
ge and giant-sized dog breeds. This is mostly because small dog breeds expe=
rience less wear and tear on their joints and major organs as they age. As =
a result, small and large dogs will experience the same life stages at diff=
erent times. Sometimes a dog=E2=80=99s breed influences this as well.</stro=
ng></p>



<p>In this article, we will be explaining everything that there is to know =
about the five major stages in a dog=E2=80=99s life. We will be explaining =
what occurs during these stages and at what age dogs of all sizes reach the=
m. We will be answering some commonly asked questions about aging in dogs a=
s well.</p>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading"><a></a>How to Figure Out Your Dog=E2=80=99s =
Age in Human Years</h2>



<p>As we have mentioned, dogs age at different rates depending on their siz=
e. Here is a helpful chart explaining how dogs age based on their size.</p>



